    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "A ScienceDaily press release claims that graphene has \"broken a fundamental law of physics\" for the first time, but the review board found the headline substantially misleading on two counts: the Wiedemann-Franz law is a Fermi-liquid approximation that was never expected to hold at graphene's Dirac point, and experimental observation of this breakdown was already reported by Crossno et al. in Science in 2016. The underlying Nature Physics paper appears to be legitimate condensed-matter research, with the credible novel contribution being the demonstration of universal quantum-of-conductance scaling and a larger violation factor achieved in cleaner samples. The most important caveat is that all conclusions here are drawn from a promotional press release with no data, error bars, or methodology \u2014 the actual paper may be solid, but cannot be assessed from this source alone.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The reviewed artifact is an IISc institutional press release, not the primary article. The plausible novel contribution of the underlying Majumdar et al. Nature Physics paper is the experimental demonstration of material-independent, quantum-of-conductance-governed scaling of both charge and heat transport at graphene's quantum-critical Dirac point, along with a reported Wiedemann-Franz Lorenz-number enhancement exceeding 200\u00d7 in ultraclean hBN-encapsulated samples \u2014 roughly 20\u00d7 larger than the ~10\u00d7 violation reported by Crossno et al. (Science 2016). The \"perfect fluid\" viscosity claim invokes the AdS/CFT-motivated KSS bound (\u03b7/s \u2265 \u210f/4\u03c0k_B) but supplies no dimensionless ratio, entropy density, or measurement protocol. All quantitative claims are unauditable from the press release; the universality and viscosity results require expert reading of the full paper and supplement."
